      {
        "callId": "79fc5855cf2c4c238e7dc6001",
        "index": 22,
        "role": "bot",
        "time": "2025-09-14T00:48:40.888000Z",
        "message": "Thanks for explaining. Um, so for you, uh, it's mainly Google. With Gemini showing up on occasion and Bing Copilot for those rewards points. When Gemini does pop up while you're searching in Google, do you notice anything distinct about its answer? Does it feel different from the usual Google results? Anything stand out?"
      },
      {
        "callId": "79fc5855cf2c4c238e7dc6001",
        "index": 23,
        "role": "user",
        "time": "2025-09-14T00:49:03.308000Z",
        "message": "It gives me sort of a rundown. And I usually click on read more or whatever the prompt is to kind of uncover the additional information, and I will skim through that. But it does because it's like a synopsis, it doesn't necessarily give me exactly what I might be after. Whereas if I go to and choose a particular site, I can drill down. And if that site doesn't give me what I want, I back out, drill down to another site. And and quite frankly, I understand the better approach with AI and chat box and engines and whatnot is to not necessarily trust that the data given are, um, 100 percent factual."
      },
      {
        "callId": "79fc5855cf2c4c238e7dc6001",
        "index": 24,
        "role": "bot",
        "time": "2025-09-14T00:49:56.318000Z",
        "message": "That's really insightful. You noticed Gemini gives a summary, but sometimes it's not as specific as you need. It's more like a starting point. When you're skimming its rundown, do you ever fact check the info or jump to websites for details? How do you handle that moment when you aren't sure if Gemini or another AI summary gave you the right answer?"
